1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,580
The first thing I noticed that morning was the silence.

2
00:00:03,220 --> 00:00:05,140
Not the silence of the vaults I knew.

3
00:00:05,660 --> 00:00:08,840
Dance, calculated, built to hide things.

4
00:00:09,340 --> 00:00:10,520
It was the good kind.

5
00:00:10,980 --> 00:00:14,160
The  kind  that  only  exists  in  rooms  where  someone  sleeps  in

6
00:00:14,160 --> 00:00:14,700
peace.

7
00:00:15,200 --> 00:00:17,500
Noelia breathed slowly beside me.

8
00:00:17,680 --> 00:00:19,520
Her hand curled up near her chin.

9
00:00:19,920 --> 00:00:23,300
The way she'd slept ever since she'd started sharing the bed with me.

10
00:00:23,580 --> 00:00:26,000
Three months, I was still counting.

11
00:00:26,540 --> 00:00:28,260
I got up without making a sound.

12
00:00:28,260 --> 00:00:31,320
The  penthouse  had  thin  blinds  that  filtered  the  light

13
00:00:31,320 --> 00:00:32,280
off  Lake  Michigan.

14
00:00:32,840 --> 00:00:36,020
And  cast  pale  patches  across  the  sheets,  long  and

15
00:00:36,020 --> 00:00:38,060
quiet  like  fingers  of  light  that  didn't

16
00:00:38,060 --> 00:00:39,040
want to wake anyone.

17
00:00:39,420 --> 00:00:41,860
I stood there for a second just to look at her.

18
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:44,280
Her chest rose and fell.

19
00:00:44,740 --> 00:00:46,340
No tension in her shoulders.

20
00:00:47,040 --> 00:00:48,540
No glinch in her jaw.

21
00:00:49,120 --> 00:00:52,140
I'd  seen  Oelia  sleep  restlessly,  dreaming  about

22
00:00:52,140 --> 00:00:53,800
the  altar,  about  Calvin.

23
00:00:53,800 --> 00:00:56,800
About the big screen that showed my face.

24
00:00:57,220 --> 00:00:57,980
Not that morning.

25
00:00:58,440 --> 00:00:59,780
It was domesticity.

26
00:01:00,080 --> 00:01:02,500
That was the word I'd never had a reason to learn.

27
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:05,240
And now it turned up all the time.

28
00:01:05,680 --> 00:01:07,280
Stuck to the smallest things.

29
00:01:07,660 --> 00:01:11,340
I put my shirt on in silence, rolled the sleeves to my elbows,

30
00:01:11,860 --> 00:01:12,860
and went to the kitchen.

31
00:01:13,420 --> 00:01:19,660
The coffee brewed quick, with that strong smell that took over the whole hallway on cold days.

32
00:01:20,060 --> 00:01:23,040
I used the chance to set the sugar bowl beside her cup.

33
00:01:23,040 --> 00:01:24,580
The way she liked it.

34
00:01:24,880 --> 00:01:26,140
Spoon already inside.

35
00:01:26,700 --> 00:01:30,480
It was ridiculous how much attention I paid to small things.

36
00:01:30,980 --> 00:01:34,940
Before her, I didn't even know there was a right position for a sugar bowl.

37
00:01:35,540 --> 00:01:37,300
Daria was waiting for me downstairs.

38
00:01:37,780 --> 00:01:41,000
I saw the car parked in the private garage when I came down.

39
00:01:41,440 --> 00:01:42,580
Armored, black.

40
00:01:43,140 --> 00:01:47,380
The window opened just enough for him to see me and tighten his expression by two millimeters.

41
00:01:48,020 --> 00:01:49,600
His way of saying good morning.

42
00:01:50,020 --> 00:01:50,260
Coffee?

43
00:01:50,960 --> 00:01:51,380
I asked.

44
00:01:51,380 --> 00:01:53,020
Already had some.

45
00:01:53,720 --> 00:01:54,320
Lyrh.

46
00:01:54,440 --> 00:01:58,140
Strange definition of a lie for someone who only asked a question.

47
00:01:58,620 --> 00:02:00,060
I got into the passenger seat.

48
00:02:00,620 --> 00:02:01,560
The meeting was early.

49
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:05,180
The casino's annex office was 20 minutes from the penthouse,

50
00:02:05,540 --> 00:02:07,760
and Masimo had confirmed the night before.

51
00:02:08,260 --> 00:02:13,980
For weeks I'd been negotiating the transfer of two casino operations to entirely legal management.

52
00:02:14,580 --> 00:02:18,480
Every signed paper was a crack I put in what I'd inherited from my father.

53
00:02:18,480 --> 00:02:21,000
It wasn't fast, it wasn't comfortable,

54
00:02:21,560 --> 00:02:26,440
but it was the only thing that felt coherent since Noelia had agreed to sleep at my side.

55
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:28,620
Does she know you're going to the casino?

56
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:31,600
Daria asked as the garage gate rose.

57
00:02:32,080 --> 00:02:33,180
I looked out the window.

58
00:02:33,680 --> 00:02:39,320
The street was still damp with cold, black puddles reflecting the street lights that hadn't gone off yet.

59
00:02:39,620 --> 00:02:40,920
I said a regular meeting.

60
00:02:41,420 --> 00:02:42,240
He didn't answer.

61
00:02:42,740 --> 00:02:44,180
It was worse than if he had.

62
00:02:44,180 --> 00:02:49,460
I knew Dario's silence is well enough to tell which frequency each one weighed on.

63
00:02:49,720 --> 00:02:51,460
That one weighed on disapproval.

64
00:02:52,020 --> 00:02:54,700
I'd promised her on the balcony her hand in mine,

65
00:02:55,220 --> 00:02:56,500
that I wouldn't lie anymore.

66
00:02:57,100 --> 00:02:59,100
And there I was, three months later,

67
00:02:59,560 --> 00:03:03,160
shaving the truth around the edges just so I wouldn't worry her.

68
00:03:03,360 --> 00:03:04,400
It was a micro-ly.

69
00:03:04,820 --> 00:03:05,600
It was harmless.

70
00:03:06,240 --> 00:03:09,660
It was exactly the kind of thing I'd sworn I would never do again.

71
00:03:10,020 --> 00:03:12,080
I clenched my jaw and looked ahead.

72
00:03:12,080 --> 00:03:16,360
The casino's annex office had the discretion only old money buys.

73
00:03:16,920 --> 00:03:22,440
Dark oak walls, low lamps, the thick carpet that muffled the sound of your own footsteps,

74
00:03:23,120 --> 00:03:26,220
and the round table my father had made before he died.

75
00:03:27,020 --> 00:03:30,700
Massimo was already seated in the same brown suit as always,

76
00:03:31,120 --> 00:03:34,880
and the smile of a man who felt at home in any room I walked into.

77
00:03:35,280 --> 00:03:38,300
He'd brought Dolce from the Italian bakery in the neighborhood,

78
00:03:38,840 --> 00:03:41,280
wrapped in wax paper that still held warmth.

79
00:03:41,280 --> 00:03:44,320
He pushed the bundle toward me when he saw me arrive.

80
00:03:45,060 --> 00:03:46,680
Eat son, you're thin.

81
00:03:47,240 --> 00:03:48,300
I haven't lost weight.

82
00:03:48,860 --> 00:03:50,060
Your mother called yesterday.

83
00:03:50,700 --> 00:03:51,380
Said you're thin.

84
00:03:51,860 --> 00:03:53,220
I believe her more than a mirror.

85
00:03:53,780 --> 00:03:54,280
I sat.

86
00:03:54,920 --> 00:03:56,820
Dario stayed standing against the door.

87
00:03:57,360 --> 00:03:58,600
Shoulder against the frame.

88
00:03:59,220 --> 00:04:01,800
Watching with that stillness that made everyone uncomfortable,

89
00:04:02,560 --> 00:04:03,360
except me.

90
00:04:03,700 --> 00:04:05,300
The meeting lasted two hours.

91
00:04:05,960 --> 00:04:08,580
Massimo questioned, with calculated gentleness,

92
00:04:08,580 --> 00:04:11,660
the speed at which I'd been legalizing the operations,

93
00:04:12,120 --> 00:04:15,100
he said he understood that he respected it,

94
00:04:15,300 --> 00:04:18,380
that he saw in me the same courage he'd seen in my father,

95
00:04:18,920 --> 00:04:22,140
but that slow was better, that the market spooked easily,

96
00:04:22,700 --> 00:04:26,460
that man loyal to me might feel betrayed if the transition was abrupt.

97
00:04:27,080 --> 00:04:29,460
Every word of his came wrapped in affection,

98
00:04:30,060 --> 00:04:32,000
that was how he always spoke to me,

99
00:04:32,200 --> 00:04:34,640
that was how he'd spoken to me my whole life.

100
00:04:35,080 --> 00:04:36,580
I nodded at several points,

101
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:38,080
disagreed at a few.

102
00:04:38,080 --> 00:04:41,940
When I left the room, the hallway was cold and smelled of the coffee,

103
00:04:42,100 --> 00:04:45,680
no one had drunk, and Dario caught up to me before I reached the door.

104
00:04:46,140 --> 00:04:47,020
You trust him.

105
00:04:47,380 --> 00:04:48,380
It wasn't a question.

106
00:04:48,900 --> 00:04:50,340
He raised me, I answered.

107
00:04:50,920 --> 00:04:52,120
That's not what I asked.

108
00:04:52,600 --> 00:04:53,400
I didn't answer.

109
00:04:53,880 --> 00:04:54,820
I got in the car.

110
00:04:55,320 --> 00:04:56,300
I checked the clock.

111
00:04:56,900 --> 00:04:59,960
Our still left before the end of Noelia's shift at the hotel,

112
00:05:00,400 --> 00:05:03,400
but the urge to have lunch with her had come out of nowhere and stayed.

113
00:05:03,840 --> 00:05:05,780
I told Dario to drive over there.

114
00:05:05,780 --> 00:05:08,480
I texted to let her know I was on my way,

115
00:05:08,700 --> 00:05:11,140
that I'd brought hunger, and nothing else.

116
00:05:11,520 --> 00:05:13,820
She replied with an emoji I couldn't describe,

117
00:05:14,400 --> 00:05:16,780
but it made me smile alone in the backseat.

118
00:05:17,240 --> 00:05:21,300
The hotel still had that clean morning smell when I came in through the service door.

119
00:05:21,900 --> 00:05:23,880
Marble, flowers changed early,

120
00:05:24,400 --> 00:05:26,120
the faint trace of floor wax.

121
00:05:26,660 --> 00:05:28,420
I took the internal elevator up.

122
00:05:28,840 --> 00:05:31,700
When the door is opened on the floor of the old vaults,

123
00:05:31,700 --> 00:05:32,180
I stopped.

124
00:05:32,720 --> 00:05:34,560
There was a maintenance crew in the hallway,

125
00:05:34,560 --> 00:05:39,960
a ladder leaning against the wall, a broken seal on one of the dark steel doors.

126
00:05:40,640 --> 00:05:42,260
The ceiling light flickered faintly,

127
00:05:42,520 --> 00:05:46,380
as if the whole floor were waking up along with whatever had been kept in there.

128
00:05:46,680 --> 00:05:48,080
The door was open.

129
00:05:48,660 --> 00:05:49,580
I knew that door.

130
00:05:50,060 --> 00:05:52,080
It was one of the oldest vaults in the building,

131
00:05:52,360 --> 00:05:57,400
from the days when the hotel still served as a private vault for city families who didn't trust banks.

132
00:05:57,960 --> 00:06:01,380
No one was authorized to open anything there without three signatures.

133
00:06:01,380 --> 00:06:04,560
I looked at the badge on the chest of the nearest employee,

134
00:06:05,100 --> 00:06:06,220
who authorized the opening.

135
00:06:06,760 --> 00:06:08,380
He looked at me, hesitated.

136
00:06:09,020 --> 00:06:11,480
The events manager, sir, missed cross.

137
00:06:12,060 --> 00:06:13,500
I walked toward the vault room.

138
00:06:13,900 --> 00:06:16,060
The hallway seemed longer than it had ever been.

139
00:06:16,500 --> 00:06:19,660
As if each step I took added another half meter to the distance.

140
00:06:20,240 --> 00:06:22,560
I'd felt this exact sensation before.

141
00:06:23,100 --> 00:06:26,680
The sensation of arriving too late to something I didn't know was happening.

142
00:06:27,180 --> 00:06:28,200
When I turned the corner,

143
00:06:28,200 --> 00:06:32,500
I saw noelia standing near a little table pushed against the wall.

144
00:06:33,020 --> 00:06:37,000
Sarai was beside her, holding a yellowed paper envelope in both hands,

145
00:06:37,540 --> 00:06:40,340
careful the way someone holds something that might break apart.

146
00:06:40,820 --> 00:06:44,640
And on top of the table, an old tape machine turned slowly.

147
00:06:45,180 --> 00:06:48,200
The tape running between two worn plastic reels.

148
00:06:48,860 --> 00:06:50,380
A voice came out of the machine.

149
00:06:50,880 --> 00:06:53,200
It was the voice of a man I didn't know,

150
00:06:53,500 --> 00:06:55,500
but I recognized the surname he spoke.

151
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:56,800
It was mine.

152
00:06:56,800 --> 00:06:59,520
The dust smelled a old paper and damp metal.

153
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:01,540
That was the smell of the vault floor.

154
00:07:02,060 --> 00:07:04,320
And I'd already been there three times that week.

155
00:07:04,780 --> 00:07:08,500
Always with the renovation plans in my hand and my head somewhere else.

156
00:07:08,840 --> 00:07:11,580
The last thing I expected was to find something real.

157
00:07:12,040 --> 00:07:13,520
This is the last one.

158
00:07:13,780 --> 00:07:17,000
Sarai said, tapping the steel door with the tip of her clipboard.

159
00:07:17,500 --> 00:07:20,120
If a literal skeleton shows up inside this vault,

160
00:07:20,600 --> 00:07:21,620
I swear I'm quitting.

161
00:07:22,180 --> 00:07:23,280
I laughed half-heartedly.

162
00:07:23,880 --> 00:07:25,380
It was one of those polite laughs.

163
00:07:25,380 --> 00:07:27,500
Just so I wouldn't ruin my friend's joke.

164
00:07:28,040 --> 00:07:30,840
Sarai was the only person who still made me laugh before coffee.

165
00:07:31,320 --> 00:07:33,480
And I knew she could tell when the laugh came out hollow.

166
00:07:33,980 --> 00:07:35,220
She didn't call me on it.

167
00:07:35,460 --> 00:07:38,120
It was the kind of friendship that doesn't need explaining to work.

168
00:07:38,600 --> 00:07:39,800
The employee turned the wheel.

169
00:07:40,280 --> 00:07:43,420
The door opened with a groan that sounded like years choked up.

170
00:07:43,760 --> 00:07:47,200
Metal contracted by time, resisting until the last second.

171
00:07:47,720 --> 00:07:48,980
Inside there was dust.

172
00:07:49,420 --> 00:07:50,380
Three yellowed folders.

173
00:07:51,060 --> 00:07:53,660
A large cassette tape inside a little plastic case.

174
00:07:53,980 --> 00:07:54,580
And an envelope.

175
00:07:54,580 --> 00:07:56,980
It was the envelope that stopped me.

176
00:07:57,160 --> 00:07:58,740
There was a name typed on the front.

177
00:07:59,240 --> 00:08:00,100
And tarot cross.

178
00:08:00,660 --> 00:08:03,500
I felt my blood dropped to somewhere it wasn't supposed to be.

179
00:08:03,680 --> 00:08:04,880
I stood still too long.

180
00:08:05,380 --> 00:08:06,640
The metal smell got stronger.

181
00:08:07,320 --> 00:08:08,520
Or I got more motionless.

182
00:08:09,020 --> 00:08:09,880
I couldn't tell which.

183
00:08:10,820 --> 00:08:11,980
Sarai looked at the envelope.

184
00:08:12,500 --> 00:08:13,260
Looked at me.

185
00:08:13,580 --> 00:08:15,260
And stopped joking in the same breath.

186
00:08:16,400 --> 00:08:16,960
No way?

187
00:08:17,800 --> 00:08:18,880
That's my father's name.

188
00:08:19,260 --> 00:08:20,960
She picked up the envelope without asking.

189
00:08:21,440 --> 00:08:22,420
I picked up the tape.

190
00:08:22,420 --> 00:08:25,820
There was a label stuck to the side of the case with a date on it.

191
00:08:26,020 --> 00:08:27,360
A date from before I was born.

192
00:08:27,840 --> 00:08:28,800
My hands were shaking.

193
00:08:29,380 --> 00:08:30,540
I told myself they weren't.

194
00:08:31,020 --> 00:08:32,000
And I looked at them.

195
00:08:32,200 --> 00:08:33,980
And they kept shaking just the same.

196
00:08:34,360 --> 00:08:36,400
Completely ignoring what I thought about the matter.

197
00:08:36,840 --> 00:08:38,660
There was an old machine in the room next door.

198
00:08:39,100 --> 00:08:40,900
One of the kind that still used tape.

199
00:08:41,300 --> 00:08:43,320
It had belonged to the hotel's previous director.

200
00:08:43,820 --> 00:08:45,480
And had never been taken off the desk.

201
00:08:45,900 --> 00:08:48,860
Forgotten between papers and an astray no one used anymore.

202
00:08:49,260 --> 00:08:51,180
I carried the tape over there without thinking.

203
00:08:51,660 --> 00:08:52,540
Sarai followed.

204
00:08:53,220 --> 00:08:54,680
Quiet for the first time in years.

205
00:08:55,220 --> 00:08:56,300
I slotted it in.

206
00:08:56,580 --> 00:08:57,360
I pressed the button.

207
00:08:57,920 --> 00:08:58,620
The tape rast.

208
00:08:59,200 --> 00:09:00,460
Then came a long hiss.

209
00:09:01,040 --> 00:09:01,780
And then the voice.

210
00:09:02,300 --> 00:09:03,880
You know who I am, Mr. Malvani.

211
00:09:04,440 --> 00:09:05,960
I'd never heard that adult voice.

212
00:09:06,440 --> 00:09:08,220
I'd heard his voice calling me to breakfast.

213
00:09:08,920 --> 00:09:10,440
Reading a children's book out loud.

214
00:09:10,960 --> 00:09:14,580
Singing happy birthday with the wrong lyrics because he thought the right ones were boring.

215
00:09:15,120 --> 00:09:18,160
I'd never heard my father's voice being the voice of a man at risk.

216
00:09:18,640 --> 00:09:19,380
But it was him.

217
00:09:19,380 --> 00:09:23,960
It was him the same way the echo of my own voice on the answering machine was me.

218
00:09:24,540 --> 00:09:26,260
Unmustocable even without a name.

219
00:09:26,740 --> 00:09:27,840
Even without context.

220
00:09:28,460 --> 00:09:30,340
I came because my family was threatened.

221
00:09:30,880 --> 00:09:33,160
He was saying his voice too firm.

222
00:09:33,540 --> 00:09:36,240
Like someone who'd rehearsed before walking into the room.

223
00:09:36,540 --> 00:09:39,760
And because you're the only man in this city who can make that threat small.

224
00:09:40,280 --> 00:09:41,240
Another voice answered.

225
00:09:41,820 --> 00:09:44,300
Old, patient, but the heavy accent.

226
00:09:44,880 --> 00:09:46,840
And the kind of calm that doesn't come from kindness.

227
00:09:47,380 --> 00:09:48,500
It asked for three names.

228
00:09:48,500 --> 00:09:50,460
My father gave the three names.

229
00:09:50,960 --> 00:09:51,900
I pressed the pause button.

230
00:09:52,440 --> 00:09:53,120
I pressed it wrong.

231
00:09:53,660 --> 00:09:54,480
The tape kept going.

232
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:55,860
He went back to the beginning.

233
00:09:56,400 --> 00:09:57,160
I heard it again.

234
00:09:57,560 --> 00:09:58,560
I didn't hear it better.

235
00:09:58,980 --> 00:09:59,860
I heard it worse.

236
00:10:00,400 --> 00:10:03,480
Because the second time I already knew what was coming and I listened anyway.

237
00:10:04,020 --> 00:10:05,620
Unable to prepare myself for anything.

238
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:07,280
I felt a hand on my shoulder.

239
00:10:07,920 --> 00:10:10,560
And it took me half a second to understand it was surreye.

240
00:10:10,840 --> 00:10:11,820
She didn't say anything.

241
00:10:12,340 --> 00:10:13,520
She was just there.

242
00:10:13,840 --> 00:10:15,480
The weight of her hand in the right place.

243
00:10:15,900 --> 00:10:17,320
The way a true friend stays.

244
00:10:17,320 --> 00:10:19,780
When there's no word that fixes it,

245
00:10:19,920 --> 00:10:22,380
that was when I noticed the third body in the room.

246
00:10:22,700 --> 00:10:23,700
I lifted my eyes.

247
00:10:24,360 --> 00:10:25,720
Everin was standing in the doorway.

248
00:10:26,560 --> 00:10:28,480
White shirt with the sleeves rolled to his elbows.

249
00:10:29,080 --> 00:10:31,140
His broad shoulders filling the frame.

250
00:10:31,520 --> 00:10:33,220
Hand braised on the side of the door.

251
00:10:33,680 --> 00:10:34,560
Eyes on me first.

252
00:10:35,100 --> 00:10:36,120
On surreye after.

253
00:10:36,660 --> 00:10:37,620
On the machine last.

254
00:10:38,120 --> 00:10:40,180
I saw the second he understood what was playing.

255
00:10:40,680 --> 00:10:41,840
I saw his jaw lock.

256
00:10:42,180 --> 00:10:45,340
I saw the way a man holds his breath without knowing he's held it.

257
00:10:45,340 --> 00:10:47,860
For three months I'd said his surname like a caress.

258
00:10:48,400 --> 00:10:50,040
I'd laughed at him when he signed papers.

259
00:10:50,560 --> 00:10:53,500
I'd whispered against his neck in the kitchen while the coffee brood.

260
00:10:53,780 --> 00:10:56,860
I'd completely forgotten what that surname was capable of doing.

261
00:10:57,420 --> 00:10:58,280
The tape kept running.

262
00:10:58,660 --> 00:11:00,760
My father's voice said the third name again.

263
00:11:01,020 --> 00:11:02,480
Clear, without hesitation.

264
00:11:03,160 --> 00:11:05,060
On a hotel floor that smelled of dust.

265
00:11:05,360 --> 00:11:07,720
And of something that shouldn't have been kept for so long.

266
00:11:08,100 --> 00:11:10,140
Surai held the envelope with the typed label.

267
00:11:10,680 --> 00:11:12,080
Everin didn't walk toward me.

268
00:11:12,400 --> 00:11:13,260
He stayed in the doorway.

269
00:11:13,260 --> 00:11:16,540
As if he knew that walking would be worse than staying still.

270
00:11:16,920 --> 00:11:18,360
I looked at him over the old machine.

271
00:11:18,860 --> 00:11:22,720
I looked at his surname written in my head in letters that suddenly carried another weight.

272
00:11:23,100 --> 00:11:26,080
For three months I'd forgotten what that surname was capable of doing.

273
00:11:26,580 --> 00:11:28,200
The tape reminded me in four minutes.

274
00:11:28,840 --> 00:11:31,120
The penthouse had a view of the lake and good silence.

275
00:11:31,660 --> 00:11:34,700
It was the first time in three months that the silence bothered me.

276
00:11:34,880 --> 00:11:39,360
I arrived with the tape inside a large envelope, holding it with both hands as if it were

277
00:11:39,360 --> 00:11:40,420
heavier than it was.

278
00:11:40,420 --> 00:11:44,700
The paper was slightly crumpled at the edges from how much I'd gripped it in the car.

279
00:11:45,100 --> 00:11:47,740
Everin had come behind me with Dario in the other vehicle.

280
00:11:48,120 --> 00:11:49,800
He didn't try to talk to me in traffic.

281
00:11:50,320 --> 00:11:53,900
When I walked into the penthouse, he was already sitting in the living room.

282
00:11:54,220 --> 00:11:58,120
Jacket open and hands clasped in his lap, waiting without hurry,

283
00:11:58,440 --> 00:11:59,740
without visible anxiety.

284
00:12:00,360 --> 00:12:01,540
He just pointed to the couch.

285
00:12:02,020 --> 00:12:03,100
Do you want to listen again?

286
00:12:03,520 --> 00:12:04,420
I want you to listen.

287
00:12:04,880 --> 00:12:09,640
I put the tape into the little tape player Dario had managed to find somewhere in the last two hours.

288
00:12:09,640 --> 00:12:15,420
The machine was old, a faded sand color, with press buttons that made a satisfying mechanical

289
00:12:15,420 --> 00:12:16,640
click when they latched.

290
00:12:17,220 --> 00:12:17,940
I pressed play.

291
00:12:18,260 --> 00:12:22,500
My father's voice came out again through that tiny speaker, slightly muffled,

292
00:12:23,020 --> 00:12:26,260
as if it were coming from inside a room that had been closed for a long time.

293
00:12:27,360 --> 00:12:31,500
With that strange quality of something recorded carefully so it wouldn't be found.

294
00:12:32,860 --> 00:12:38,260
Everin listened without moving, without commenting, without crossing his arms or looking

295
00:12:38,260 --> 00:12:40,740
away or trying to protect me from what I already knew.

296
00:12:42,160 --> 00:12:43,620
When it ended, he stayed silent.

297
00:12:45,180 --> 00:12:47,860
The kind of silence that isn't an absence of an answer.

298
00:12:48,820 --> 00:12:49,440
It's an answer.

299
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:50,460
Say something.

300
00:12:51,080 --> 00:12:53,300
Whatever you want me to say is going to sound like a defense.

301
00:12:53,860 --> 00:12:55,800
I'm not going to defend myself from this.

302
00:12:56,040 --> 00:12:57,380
You breathe in deep slowly.

303
00:12:57,940 --> 00:12:59,020
I don't know this tape.

304
00:12:59,460 --> 00:13:00,100
It's your surname.

305
00:13:00,680 --> 00:13:01,080
I know.

306
00:13:01,560 --> 00:13:02,180
It's my father.

307
00:13:02,700 --> 00:13:03,200
I know.

308
00:13:03,600 --> 00:13:04,480
So what do you know?

309
00:13:04,720 --> 00:13:05,880
He took a while to answer.

310
00:13:05,880 --> 00:13:10,280
He looked at the floor for a second and then looked at me with an expression I was still

311
00:13:10,280 --> 00:13:11,040
learning to read.

312
00:13:11,480 --> 00:13:12,280
It wasn't regret.

313
00:13:12,840 --> 00:13:13,860
It wasn't an apology.

314
00:13:14,460 --> 00:13:16,160
It was something more honest than both.

315
00:13:16,560 --> 00:13:20,840
It was the face of a man who grew up without the luxury of pretending the world was simple.

316
00:13:21,300 --> 00:13:23,920
That this happened before I existed as a melvani.

317
00:13:24,440 --> 00:13:27,260
And that if you need space, I'll give it to you.

318
00:13:27,480 --> 00:13:28,600
I asked for space.

319
00:13:29,120 --> 00:13:29,860
He gave it.

320
00:13:30,100 --> 00:13:31,280
Wednesday passed slowly.

321
00:13:31,820 --> 00:13:35,720
I slept in the guest room with the window a jar and the sound of the lake arriving

322
00:13:35,720 --> 00:13:37,860
in low waves that couldn't fill the room.

323
00:13:38,120 --> 00:13:41,120
The mattress was too firm and smelled faintly of artificial lavender.

324
00:13:41,700 --> 00:13:43,700
That hotel scent that was supposed to be comforting.

325
00:13:44,340 --> 00:13:47,700
But that night only reminded me I was sleeping in a room that wasn't mine.

326
00:13:48,180 --> 00:13:50,380
Inside an apartment that still felt like his.

327
00:13:51,740 --> 00:13:53,980
I crossed paths with ever and twice in the hallway.

328
00:13:55,240 --> 00:13:58,900
One of those times his hair was wet and his shirt was open at the first button.

329
00:13:59,560 --> 00:14:03,940
And both times he looked away with a politeness that hurt me more than if he'd insisted on talking.

330
00:14:04,680 --> 00:14:07,160
There was something in his care that weighed.

331
00:14:07,440 --> 00:14:10,580
As if keeping his distance were the greatest effort he'd ever made.

332
00:14:10,960 --> 00:14:15,840
Thursday morning, Sarai showed up with coffee in a giant croissant wrapped in parchment paper.

333
00:14:16,380 --> 00:14:17,080
Still warm.

334
00:14:17,540 --> 00:14:20,320
The heat of the bundle passed through my hands when she set it on the counter.

335
00:14:20,900 --> 00:14:22,640
And for a moment I just stared at it.

336
00:14:22,940 --> 00:14:25,380
As if the whole gesture were too complicated to receive.

337
00:14:25,880 --> 00:14:26,600
I brought carbs.

338
00:14:27,040 --> 00:14:28,100
I didn't bring good sense.

339
00:14:28,620 --> 00:14:29,560
That's already a start.

340
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:32,860
She sat on the kitchen counter and crossed her arms over the ledge.

341
00:14:32,860 --> 00:14:36,400
With the posture of someone who was going to stay there as long as needed.

342
00:14:36,860 --> 00:14:40,380
She looked at the TV in the living room, which was on with no sound.

343
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:42,820
I didn't even know why I'd turned it on.

344
00:14:43,260 --> 00:14:48,740
I'd turned it on because the silence of the penthouse became a concrete thing inside my chest if I let it grow.

345
00:14:49,440 --> 00:14:49,500
No.

346
00:14:50,760 --> 00:14:51,520
Look at the screen.

347
00:14:52,060 --> 00:14:52,500
I looked.

348
00:14:52,800 --> 00:14:54,960
It was the logo of the local gossip radio.

349
00:14:55,540 --> 00:14:57,960
The one I always pretended not to listen to.

350
00:14:58,200 --> 00:15:02,840
But the two hosts plain studio in the background and a central microphone they used for everything.

351
00:15:02,860 --> 00:15:06,300
From neighborhood squabbles to national scandal.

352
00:15:06,840 --> 00:15:07,820
The headline underneath.

353
00:15:08,520 --> 00:15:09,640
In yellow capital letters.

354
00:15:10,080 --> 00:15:11,180
Took up half the screen.

355
00:15:11,880 --> 00:15:15,100
Criminal informants daughter organized the gala of the year.

356
00:15:15,500 --> 00:15:17,860
Sorai pressed the remote and turned up the volume.

357
00:15:18,500 --> 00:15:20,240
A piece of the tape played on the air.

358
00:15:20,520 --> 00:15:21,240
It was short.

359
00:15:21,720 --> 00:15:22,680
Maybe 40 seconds.

360
00:15:23,200 --> 00:15:25,860
It was exactly the part where my father gave the second name.

361
00:15:26,200 --> 00:15:27,200
There was no context.

362
00:15:27,760 --> 00:15:29,300
There was no story before it.

363
00:15:29,560 --> 00:15:32,080
There was none of the part where his voice grew more tense.

364
00:15:32,080 --> 00:15:34,720
As if he were choosing his words very carefully.

365
00:15:35,260 --> 00:15:36,920
As if the situation weren't simple.

366
00:15:37,980 --> 00:15:38,680
There was nothing.

367
00:15:39,780 --> 00:15:41,900
It was just his voice saying a man's name.

368
00:15:42,480 --> 00:15:44,100
Clean and alone on the air.

369
00:15:44,600 --> 00:15:47,720
Dry as an accusation that already arrived with the verdict ready.

370
00:15:49,020 --> 00:15:49,140
How?

371
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:50,520
I asked.

372
00:15:50,860 --> 00:15:52,280
Sorai didn't answer right away.

373
00:15:52,680 --> 00:15:54,420
There was a slight tightening in her jaw.

374
00:15:54,920 --> 00:15:56,640
The sign I knew for contained anger.

375
00:15:57,160 --> 00:15:57,900
I don't know.

376
00:15:58,140 --> 00:15:59,240
But I'm going to find out.

377
00:15:59,560 --> 00:16:01,320
I got up and walked to the living room window.

378
00:16:01,320 --> 00:16:02,880
The lake was calm.

379
00:16:03,320 --> 00:16:05,200
A cold gray blue autumn morning.

380
00:16:05,700 --> 00:16:08,120
With a few small boats too far off to identify.

381
00:16:08,720 --> 00:16:12,180
And a thin mist near the shore that made everything slightly imprecise.

382
00:16:12,620 --> 00:16:14,480
Like a photo taken with the wrong lens.

383
00:16:14,980 --> 00:16:19,180
I thought about how many people were listening to that sentence from my father at that exact moment.

384
00:16:19,580 --> 00:16:20,140
In cars.

385
00:16:20,560 --> 00:16:21,480
In the coffee line.

386
00:16:21,940 --> 00:16:23,400
In the dentist's waiting room.

387
00:16:23,700 --> 00:16:24,660
In the office elevator.

388
00:16:25,280 --> 00:16:28,820
I thought about the hotel sponsors hearing it on the way to the 10 o'clock meeting.

389
00:16:28,820 --> 00:16:31,540
I thought about the parents of my school classmates.

390
00:16:32,200 --> 00:16:34,580
People who had known my father at neighborhood dinners.

391
00:16:35,100 --> 00:16:38,600
People who would swear now that they'd always suspected something about him.

392
00:16:38,720 --> 00:16:40,100
They cut everything that mattered.

393
00:16:40,800 --> 00:16:41,080
I said.

394
00:16:41,560 --> 00:16:43,060
Those creeps live off this.

395
00:16:43,420 --> 00:16:44,380
It's diaper journalism.

396
00:16:45,100 --> 00:16:45,660
Dirty it.

397
00:16:45,780 --> 00:16:46,360
Throw it out.

398
00:16:46,640 --> 00:16:47,600
Dirty another one.

399
00:16:47,940 --> 00:16:48,460
I laughed.

400
00:16:48,980 --> 00:16:50,580
It was a dry, short laugh.

401
00:16:50,980 --> 00:16:53,240
The kind that comes before crying if I'm not careful.

402
00:16:53,860 --> 00:16:56,100
Sorai came to me and squeezed my hand over the counter.

403
00:16:56,620 --> 00:16:58,200
You need to get out of here for a while.

404
00:16:58,200 --> 00:16:59,080
I left.

405
00:16:59,640 --> 00:17:00,780
I went to the old apartment.

406
00:17:01,400 --> 00:17:03,280
The apartment where I'd lived before the gala.

407
00:17:03,800 --> 00:17:06,260
Where I'd made the dumbest decision of my adult life.

408
00:17:06,660 --> 00:17:09,560
Eiring an escort because I was afraid of being looked at with pity.

409
00:17:10,020 --> 00:17:11,640
The apartment was still in my name.

410
00:17:12,020 --> 00:17:13,920
I hadn't been able to hand back the key.

411
00:17:14,320 --> 00:17:16,260
There was something superstitious in it.

412
00:17:16,540 --> 00:17:20,100
In keeping a piece of myself stored in a place where no one could reach me.

413
00:17:20,320 --> 00:17:21,200
I opened the door.

414
00:17:21,640 --> 00:17:23,120
The smell of stale air.

415
00:17:23,540 --> 00:17:25,740
And of an old perfume I no longer wore.

416
00:17:25,740 --> 00:17:28,260
Baintly sweet and a little suffocating.

417
00:17:28,820 --> 00:17:32,880
With that added layer of dust places gather when they go a long time without breathing.

418
00:17:33,360 --> 00:17:35,160
The furniture was covered with white sheets.

419
00:17:35,620 --> 00:17:38,800
And the light coming through the shutters created stripes on the wood floor.

420
00:17:39,260 --> 00:17:40,940
I walked straight to the hallway closet.

421
00:17:41,440 --> 00:17:42,420
Open the bottom drawer.

422
00:17:42,920 --> 00:17:44,660
And took out my father's box of photos.

423
00:17:45,240 --> 00:17:46,220
I sat on the floor.

424
00:17:46,680 --> 00:17:50,220
There were birthday photos and vacation photos and Sunday morning photos.

425
00:17:50,720 --> 00:17:53,120
There was a photo of him carrying me in his arms.

426
00:17:53,120 --> 00:17:54,200
On the beach.

427
00:17:54,680 --> 00:17:56,560
With a floppy straw hat on his head.

428
00:17:56,840 --> 00:17:58,940
And his eyes half closed from all the sun.

429
00:17:59,300 --> 00:18:02,360
There was the yellow dress he'd bought me in some small town market.

430
00:18:02,760 --> 00:18:05,800
Bulled it at the bottom of the box because I'd never been able to throw it away.

431
00:18:06,280 --> 00:18:07,720
The fabric was slightly faded.

432
00:18:08,140 --> 00:18:11,540
With a permanent crease down the center where it had been rolled up for years.

433
00:18:11,920 --> 00:18:17,020
And as I ran my fingers across the surface I thought that faded yellow was the most his thing I still had.

434
00:18:17,460 --> 00:18:20,500
And underneath the dress, I found the birthday cassette tape.

435
00:18:20,960 --> 00:18:22,120
I remembered right away.

436
00:18:22,120 --> 00:18:25,040
He'd recorded an entire tape for my 12th birthday.

437
00:18:25,580 --> 00:18:26,280
He'd sung.

438
00:18:26,720 --> 00:18:27,760
Read a piece of a book.

439
00:18:28,260 --> 00:18:33,580
Sent a message to my future self with that ceremonial seriousness he put into things he considered important.

440
00:18:34,180 --> 00:18:37,240
I hadn't listened to the tape a single time in over 20 years.

441
00:18:37,600 --> 00:18:40,400
I was afraid his voice would come out different from what I remembered.

442
00:18:41,040 --> 00:18:42,100
Thenner, stranger,

443
00:18:42,900 --> 00:18:44,500
Deformed by time or by memory.

444
00:18:44,980 --> 00:18:46,940
There was a portable tape player in the box.

445
00:18:47,500 --> 00:18:49,000
Smaller than the palm of my hand.

446
00:18:49,480 --> 00:18:50,620
The battery still worked.

447
00:18:50,620 --> 00:18:54,200
I slotted the tape in carefully as if the plastic were fragile.

448
00:18:54,680 --> 00:18:57,340
As if the wrong pressure could erase what was stored inside.

449
00:18:57,840 --> 00:18:58,640
I pressed the button.

450
00:18:59,120 --> 00:19:00,960
His voice came out singing happy birthday.

451
00:19:01,520 --> 00:19:02,680
It was the same voice.

452
00:19:03,260 --> 00:19:04,120
The same texture.

453
00:19:04,740 --> 00:19:05,860
The same slight rasp.

454
00:19:06,300 --> 00:19:11,000
The same way of holding the A at the end of words as if each syllable needed more room than usual.

455
00:19:11,440 --> 00:19:13,080
It was the voice from the vault tape.

456
00:19:13,520 --> 00:19:16,240
It was the voice of every Sunday morning of my childhood.

457
00:19:16,820 --> 00:19:19,740
Of the breakfast table with the big cup that was always his.

458
00:19:19,740 --> 00:19:24,860
Of the dark hallway when he checked whether I was asleep before turning off the living room light.

459
00:19:25,340 --> 00:19:26,300
I started to cry.

460
00:19:26,760 --> 00:19:28,480
The way I hadn't cried since the altar.

461
00:19:29,020 --> 00:19:29,580
No sound.

462
00:19:30,100 --> 00:19:30,720
No performance.

463
00:19:31,360 --> 00:19:34,480
My hand flat on my chest as if I needed to hold something in.

464
00:19:34,640 --> 00:19:36,440
I sat on the floor of the empty apartment.

465
00:19:37,060 --> 00:19:38,940
With the stripes of light across my back.

466
00:19:39,260 --> 00:19:41,200
The smell of stale air all around.

467
00:19:41,780 --> 00:19:44,960
Listening to my father sing happy birthday to me at 12 years old.

468
00:19:45,340 --> 00:19:49,540
And I kept thinking about the moment he'd had to choose between protecting me and continuing to

469
00:19:49,540 --> 00:19:51,420
look like a simple man in my eyes.

470
00:19:51,760 --> 00:19:52,740
Whether he'd hesitated.

471
00:19:53,320 --> 00:19:54,960
Whether it had been easy or impossible.

472
00:19:55,700 --> 00:19:57,620
Whether he knew in that birthday recording.

473
00:19:58,240 --> 00:19:59,340
What he'd already done.

474
00:19:59,800 --> 00:20:01,600
Sarai came to get me in the late afternoon.

475
00:20:02,200 --> 00:20:03,260
She didn't ask anything.

476
00:20:03,840 --> 00:20:06,160
Which was the most generous gesture she could have offered.

477
00:20:06,660 --> 00:20:07,960
I went back to the penthouse.

478
00:20:08,440 --> 00:20:09,680
The lake was already dark.

479
00:20:10,080 --> 00:20:15,240
The boat lights reflecting on the water and crooked trembling lines that dissolved as soon as the wind passed.

480
00:20:15,660 --> 00:20:16,480
I went in.

481
00:20:16,840 --> 00:20:17,880
Everin was in the kitchen.

482
00:20:17,880 --> 00:20:20,000
Sleeve still rolled to his elbow.

483
00:20:20,580 --> 00:20:24,040
Making something in a pan that he turned off when he heard me arrive.

484
00:20:24,520 --> 00:20:25,300
A quiet movement.

485
00:20:25,940 --> 00:20:26,420
Unhurried.

486
00:20:26,960 --> 00:20:29,820
As if he'd been waiting for this hour without admitting he was waiting.

487
00:20:30,320 --> 00:20:33,980
He looked at me with the kind of look that asks for nothing and promises nothing.

488
00:20:34,560 --> 00:20:35,360
It just receives.

489
00:20:36,080 --> 00:20:38,260
I'm going to sleep in the guest room one more night.

490
00:20:38,740 --> 00:20:39,300
That's fine.

491
00:20:39,840 --> 00:20:40,960
It's not because of you.

492
00:20:41,440 --> 00:20:42,000
I know.

493
00:20:42,380 --> 00:20:43,400
I walked down the hallway.

494
00:20:43,960 --> 00:20:44,880
I stopped halfway.

495
00:20:44,880 --> 00:20:47,540
The wood floor was cold under my socks.

496
00:20:47,940 --> 00:20:52,840
And the hallway had that late night dimness that made everything a little more honest than during the day.

497
00:20:53,080 --> 00:20:53,980
I went back.

498
00:20:54,360 --> 00:20:54,720
Everin.

499
00:20:55,900 --> 00:20:57,520
Thank you for not trying to fix it.

500
00:20:57,720 --> 00:20:59,120
He lowered his eyes for a moment.

501
00:20:59,560 --> 00:21:00,700
And he looked at me again.

502
00:21:01,040 --> 00:21:02,460
There was something different there.

503
00:21:02,740 --> 00:21:03,280
Not hurt.

504
00:21:03,760 --> 00:21:04,420
Not resignation.

505
00:21:05,100 --> 00:21:06,040
But a kind of calm.

506
00:21:06,540 --> 00:21:07,440
The cost dearly.

507
00:21:07,780 --> 00:21:10,420
The kind of calm he must have learned the worst way possible.

508
00:21:10,800 --> 00:21:12,260
I don't know how to fix this.

509
00:21:12,540 --> 00:21:12,960
I know.

510
00:21:13,460 --> 00:21:14,040
That's why.

511
00:21:14,040 --> 00:21:16,220
That night, before lying down,

512
00:21:16,420 --> 00:21:19,700
I went through the hotel lobby to pick up a folder I'd left in the office.

513
00:21:20,120 --> 00:21:21,340
The reception was quiet.

514
00:21:21,840 --> 00:21:26,540
Only one clerk at the desk and the reduced late night lighting that made the marble floor warmer than

515
00:21:26,540 --> 00:21:27,340
during the day.

516
00:21:27,700 --> 00:21:30,020
The neighborhood paper was folded on top of the counter.

517
00:21:30,540 --> 00:21:31,300
A small headline.

518
00:21:31,840 --> 00:21:33,460
In the lower corner of the front page.

519
00:21:33,980 --> 00:21:35,540
Calvin Harth was going to trial.

520
00:21:35,980 --> 00:21:37,100
I looked for two seconds.

521
00:21:37,640 --> 00:21:38,580
I didn't feel anger.

522
00:21:39,140 --> 00:21:40,120
I didn't feel relief.

523
00:21:40,640 --> 00:21:42,020
I didn't feel anything concrete.

524
00:21:42,020 --> 00:21:45,840
Which was strange after so many months waiting for exactly that headline.

525
00:21:46,400 --> 00:21:49,960
It was as if it had turned small inside me without my noticing when.

526
00:21:51,240 --> 00:21:53,340
I put the paper back in its place and left.

527
00:21:54,340 --> 00:21:56,200
I got back to the penthouse close to 11.

528
00:21:57,200 --> 00:21:58,720
Ever and had already laying down.

529
00:21:59,060 --> 00:22:01,260
Or had the delicacy to pretend he had.

530
00:22:02,140 --> 00:22:03,660
I took off my shoes in the hallway.

531
00:22:04,280 --> 00:22:04,560
Slowly.

532
00:22:05,240 --> 00:22:06,220
So I wouldn't make noise.

533
00:22:06,740 --> 00:22:07,900
I went to the guest room.

534
00:22:08,220 --> 00:22:09,820
I laid down with the window a jar.

535
00:22:09,820 --> 00:22:13,940
The cold off the late coming in and thin waves that barely moved the curtain.

536
00:22:14,400 --> 00:22:15,260
The doorbell rang.

537
00:22:15,760 --> 00:22:17,340
I looked at the clock on the nightstand.

538
00:22:17,980 --> 00:22:18,980
11.04.

539
00:22:19,440 --> 00:22:21,360
No one showed up at that penthouse unannounced.

540
00:22:21,900 --> 00:22:24,800
Dario filtered everything, including late night visitors.

541
00:22:25,480 --> 00:22:28,180
Unless it was someone Dario couldn't filter for another reason.

542
00:22:28,680 --> 00:22:29,600
I got up.

543
00:22:29,840 --> 00:22:31,780
I walked to the entrance monitor in the hallway.

544
00:22:32,300 --> 00:22:35,000
There was a woman standing downstairs in the camera's frame.

545
00:22:35,480 --> 00:22:37,340
Dark heavy coat, straight shoulders.

546
00:22:37,340 --> 00:22:41,100
Grey hair pulled into a low bun with a firmness that seemed deliberate.

547
00:22:41,660 --> 00:22:43,680
She wasn't looking at the inner com or the camera.

548
00:22:44,280 --> 00:22:48,460
She was looking straight ahead with the specific patience of someone who knows she's going to be

549
00:22:48,460 --> 00:22:48,940
let in.

550
00:22:49,820 --> 00:22:54,340
When she lifted her eyes to the monitor, I recognized her without ever having seen her before.

551
00:22:54,740 --> 00:22:58,820
They were black firm eyes that I knew from every morning of the last three months on someone

552
00:22:58,820 --> 00:22:59,640
else's face.

553
00:23:00,020 --> 00:23:01,900
I pressed the inner com with a trembling hand.

554
00:23:02,460 --> 00:23:02,760
Yes?

555
00:23:03,240 --> 00:23:05,520
Her voice came weighted with a light Italian accent.

556
00:23:06,200 --> 00:23:08,160
Precise without affectation.

557
00:23:08,500 --> 00:23:09,060
Miss Cross.

558
00:23:09,680 --> 00:23:10,520
I am Bruno Melvani.

559
00:23:11,020 --> 00:23:14,360
I need to tell you something about your father before my son finds out on his own.

560
00:23:14,760 --> 00:23:19,620
The doorbell buzzed again, and the sound pushed me toward the door before I decided to open it.

561
00:23:19,860 --> 00:23:21,240
Everyone was already in the hallway.

562
00:23:21,920 --> 00:23:22,400
Barefoot.

563
00:23:22,660 --> 00:23:24,820
Black shirt wrinkled like a man who hadn't slept.

564
00:23:25,460 --> 00:23:27,000
His eyes met mine for a second.

565
00:23:27,480 --> 00:23:28,360
A long second.

566
00:23:28,780 --> 00:23:31,080
Waded with a question neither of us put into words.

567
00:23:31,560 --> 00:23:32,920
He didn't ask who it was.

568
00:23:33,380 --> 00:23:34,440
Maybe he already knew.

569
00:23:34,440 --> 00:23:39,280
I opened the penthouse door, and the woman waiting on the other side took off her coat with

570
00:23:39,280 --> 00:23:43,420
the delicacy of someone entering a home for the first time without being sure she'd be welcome.

571
00:23:43,980 --> 00:23:44,880
60 something.

572
00:23:45,360 --> 00:23:47,060
Gray hair pulled into a low bun.

573
00:23:47,560 --> 00:23:49,360
Discrete lipstick invaded wine.

574
00:23:49,760 --> 00:23:52,640
A thin chain of old gold resting on the skin of her chest.

575
00:23:52,960 --> 00:23:55,120
The Italian accent appeared in the first word.

576
00:23:55,640 --> 00:23:58,140
Light like the smoke still rising from the kitchen coffee.

577
00:23:58,660 --> 00:24:00,160
The one I'd forgotten to turn off.

578
00:24:00,480 --> 00:24:01,500
May I come in, Noelia?

579
00:24:02,080 --> 00:24:03,000
She knew my name.

580
00:24:03,000 --> 00:24:07,340
She knew enough to wait until 11 at night at the entrance of a building that wasn't hers.

581
00:24:07,760 --> 00:24:11,520
With late cold outside and a discretion that told me more than any introduction.

582
00:24:12,180 --> 00:24:12,620
You may.

583
00:24:13,080 --> 00:24:13,540
My answered.

584
00:24:14,180 --> 00:24:15,060
And step to side.

585
00:24:15,660 --> 00:24:17,540
Ever and approach to his mother from the inside.

586
00:24:18,100 --> 00:24:19,080
Without touching her.

587
00:24:19,420 --> 00:24:21,780
The two exchanged a short, dry look.

588
00:24:22,220 --> 00:24:24,360
And I realized that between them too.

589
00:24:24,640 --> 00:24:25,800
There were old silences.

590
00:24:26,340 --> 00:24:29,040
The kind carried for decades without needing words.

591
00:24:29,600 --> 00:24:31,680
Because the words wouldn't ease anything anyway.

592
00:24:31,680 --> 00:24:34,940
Bruno Melvani set her purse on the coffee table carefully.

593
00:24:35,560 --> 00:24:36,740
As if the gesture mattered.

594
00:24:37,280 --> 00:24:39,780
And looked at me with a calm that hurt more than any hurry.

595
00:24:40,240 --> 00:24:42,320
I came before he found out on his own.

596
00:24:42,600 --> 00:24:43,340
She said.

597
00:24:43,640 --> 00:24:45,120
Tilting her head toward her son.

598
00:24:45,600 --> 00:24:49,460
There are things about your father that I had to keep for more than 20 years.

599
00:24:49,840 --> 00:24:53,240
And that are now coming out of a vault I believed no longer existed.

600
00:24:54,360 --> 00:24:55,720
I felt my stomach tightened.

601
00:24:56,960 --> 00:24:58,220
Bruno sat on the couch.

602
00:24:58,220 --> 00:25:00,680
Smooth her dark skirt over her knees.

603
00:25:01,360 --> 00:25:02,980
And waited for me to sit too.

604
00:25:03,820 --> 00:25:06,740
The apartment was quiet except for the low wind at the windows.

605
00:25:07,760 --> 00:25:08,900
Ever in stayed standing.

606
00:25:09,620 --> 00:25:11,000
Leaning against the kitchen counter.

607
00:25:11,680 --> 00:25:12,820
Two steps behind us.

608
00:25:13,940 --> 00:25:14,820
He didn't interrupt.

609
00:25:15,940 --> 00:25:17,660
In that house, that night.

610
00:25:18,120 --> 00:25:19,500
The voice belonged to his mother.

611
00:25:20,020 --> 00:25:22,860
And tarot cross came to my husband 22 years ago.

612
00:25:23,220 --> 00:25:27,120
Bruno began slowly, choosing each word like someone crossing thin ice.

613
00:25:27,120 --> 00:25:29,140
Not to sell anyone out.

614
00:25:29,360 --> 00:25:30,100
To infiltrate.

615
00:25:30,600 --> 00:25:34,380
There was a dissident faction that had started threatening entire families by name.

616
00:25:34,840 --> 00:25:38,900
Your mother and you were on a list that reached your father's hands from inside a department he

617
00:25:38,900 --> 00:25:39,180
coordinated.

618
00:25:39,800 --> 00:25:40,740
He had two choices.

619
00:25:41,340 --> 00:25:45,120
Get you out of the country and lose you another way or agree to go in.

620
00:25:45,480 --> 00:25:48,320
The coffee cup on the coffee table stopped existing for me.

621
00:25:48,620 --> 00:25:52,560
I heard Bruno's breathing louder than any sound coming from the building or the street.

622
00:25:52,960 --> 00:25:53,600
He agreed.

623
00:25:54,220 --> 00:25:54,900
She went on.

624
00:25:54,900 --> 00:25:57,600
He arranged a staged handover with the old Melvani.

625
00:25:58,240 --> 00:26:01,320
And tarot would give three names that were already technically dead.

626
00:26:01,660 --> 00:26:03,540
From the standpoint of the family's accounting.

627
00:26:04,220 --> 00:26:07,040
And in exchange the dissidence would believe he was with them.

628
00:26:07,300 --> 00:26:08,420
It was a long game.

629
00:26:08,820 --> 00:26:10,920
The plan was to expose everything in the end.

630
00:26:11,320 --> 00:26:12,980
With names and dates and faces.

631
00:26:13,660 --> 00:26:15,000
The old Melvani knew.

632
00:26:15,320 --> 00:26:15,860
I knew.

633
00:26:16,260 --> 00:26:20,060
For years, it was the most expensive secret of my marriage.

634
00:26:20,540 --> 00:26:21,780
The three men who died.

635
00:26:22,280 --> 00:26:24,000
My voice came out almost breathless.

636
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:28,260
They died because someone from inside our family sold the plan ahead of time.

637
00:26:28,560 --> 00:26:30,940
It wasn't your father's tape that killed those men.

638
00:26:31,320 --> 00:26:32,660
It was internal betrayal.

639
00:26:33,360 --> 00:26:35,260
On tarot found out who had sold them out.

640
00:26:35,640 --> 00:26:37,680
He was going to expose it in both directions.

641
00:26:38,320 --> 00:26:39,860
To the dissidence to the police.

642
00:26:40,280 --> 00:26:41,860
He was killed before he could.

643
00:26:42,260 --> 00:26:43,280
I lifted my eyes.

644
00:26:43,720 --> 00:26:44,180
She waited.

645
00:26:44,700 --> 00:26:46,580
I needed to hear the name from her mouth.

646
00:26:47,020 --> 00:26:47,940
And she knew it.

647
00:26:48,220 --> 00:26:51,560
New it the same way you know when someone is holding a door from the inside.

648
00:26:51,560 --> 00:26:54,160
Waiting for someone on the other side to push.

649
00:26:54,800 --> 00:26:55,660
Massimo Grell.

650
00:26:56,040 --> 00:26:56,560
Bruno said.

651
00:26:57,100 --> 00:26:58,700
It was Massimo who killed your father.

652
00:26:59,200 --> 00:27:01,460
And my husband died in the ambush that followed.

653
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:04,800
Precisely because Massimo passed our movements to the dissidence.

654
00:27:05,320 --> 00:27:08,920
In one week, he had the two widows he needed to control what was left.

655
00:27:09,540 --> 00:27:10,220
Behind me.

656
00:27:10,460 --> 00:27:13,140
I heard the sound of ever and breathing slowly through his nose.

657
00:27:13,640 --> 00:27:16,200
Like someone holding an entire wave inside his chest.

658
00:27:16,600 --> 00:27:18,240
So as not to knock the room down.

659
00:27:18,640 --> 00:27:19,860
Why did you never tell?

660
00:27:19,860 --> 00:27:20,740
I asked.

661
00:27:21,220 --> 00:27:24,820
Because as long as Massimo thought I didn't know, he kept me alive.

662
00:27:25,440 --> 00:27:26,020
Bruno answered.

663
00:27:26,600 --> 00:27:27,900
Without looking away from me.

664
00:27:28,200 --> 00:27:32,480
And as long as Everin believed in the father figure Massimo built over two decades.

665
00:27:33,240 --> 00:27:35,420
Massimo wouldn't need to kill my son too.

666
00:27:35,620 --> 00:27:36,480
I looked at Everin.

667
00:27:36,940 --> 00:27:37,540
He was still.

668
00:27:38,140 --> 00:27:39,800
Hand closed over the stone counter.

669
00:27:40,360 --> 00:27:42,280
His knuckles white against the dark granite.

670
00:27:42,720 --> 00:27:43,500
He said nothing.

671
00:27:44,040 --> 00:27:45,300
He only tilted his head.

672
00:27:45,720 --> 00:27:45,900
Slowly.

673
00:27:46,560 --> 00:27:49,660
Like someone recognizing a pain that had already been inside him

674
00:27:49,660 --> 00:27:53,960
for a long time, waiting to be named by someone who survived to name it.

675
00:27:54,260 --> 00:27:55,180
Bruno stood up.

676
00:27:55,440 --> 00:27:59,000
She ran her hand across my face with a lightness that didn't ask permission.

677
00:27:59,560 --> 00:28:00,440
And even so.

678
00:28:00,740 --> 00:28:01,740
Didn't invade anything.

679
00:28:02,280 --> 00:28:06,620
It was the gesture of a woman who had learned the difference between consoling and invading.

680
00:28:07,160 --> 00:28:08,980
Your father died protecting you, Noelia.

681
00:28:09,660 --> 00:28:11,360
The old vault held the wrong tape.

682
00:28:11,900 --> 00:28:13,860
Somewhere, there's a complete tape.

683
00:28:14,240 --> 00:28:16,160
The one where he explains everything in detail.

684
00:28:16,160 --> 00:28:19,320
With the plan, the names, and the intentions.

685
00:28:20,020 --> 00:28:21,780
Massimo spent 22 years looking.

686
00:28:22,280 --> 00:28:24,840
If he learns that the tape from the envelope reached the hotel,

687
00:28:25,300 --> 00:28:26,360
he'll come after the rest.

688
00:28:26,740 --> 00:28:28,020
And he'll come after me first.

689
00:28:28,480 --> 00:28:30,660
She picked up the purse from the center of the table.

690
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:33,320
Everin finally moved to walk her to the door.

691
00:28:33,740 --> 00:28:36,960
His mother placed an open hand on her son's chest for two seconds.

692
00:28:37,560 --> 00:28:38,380
Just two.

693
00:28:38,660 --> 00:28:41,380
Like someone touching a wall to feel whether it's still standing.

694
00:28:42,020 --> 00:28:43,560
Whether the material still holds.

695
00:28:44,080 --> 00:28:45,360
I'm not going home tonight.

696
00:28:45,360 --> 00:28:49,100
She said to him, her voice low and firm without drama.

697
00:28:49,640 --> 00:28:51,160
I'll get a room far from here.

698
00:28:51,460 --> 00:28:52,680
No one needs to know where.

699
00:28:53,100 --> 00:28:54,460
The door closed behind her.

700
00:28:54,720 --> 00:28:57,300
The sound of the latch was the only noise in the whole apartment.

701
00:28:57,840 --> 00:28:59,260
I stayed sitting on the couch.

702
00:28:59,760 --> 00:29:03,540
Even stayed in the same place, leaning against the counter without turning around.

703
00:29:04,360 --> 00:29:05,960
I went to the kitchen when she left.

704
00:29:06,380 --> 00:29:07,320
It wasn't fleeing.

705
00:29:07,880 --> 00:29:11,960
It was the only wall in the house where I could stay standing without looking at Noelia.

706
00:29:11,960 --> 00:29:15,420
While my world finished falling in orderly silence.

707
00:29:16,200 --> 00:29:17,020
Peace by peace.

708
00:29:17,560 --> 00:29:20,020
Like a structure collapsing from the inside out.

709
00:29:20,400 --> 00:29:22,580
I turned on the faucet just for the sound.

710
00:29:23,060 --> 00:29:27,400
I braised both hands on the cold stone counter and closed my eyes.

711
00:29:27,860 --> 00:29:30,260
The first thing that came wasn't Massimo.

712
00:29:30,720 --> 00:29:31,720
It was her.

713
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:33,240
Backstage at the hotel.

714
00:29:33,720 --> 00:29:34,560
Three months ago.

715
00:29:34,940 --> 00:29:38,540
The hallway smelled of expensive flowers and a electrical cable

716
00:29:38,540 --> 00:29:41,720
heated by the spotlights to set up crew had left on.

717
00:29:42,040 --> 00:29:44,320
I'd come in through the service door as arranged.

718
00:29:44,920 --> 00:29:47,000
The false name on the tip of my tongue.

719
00:29:47,520 --> 00:29:49,940
The crest ring in the inner pocket of my jacket.

720
00:29:50,580 --> 00:29:53,400
Away from my right hand for the first time in years.

721
00:29:53,740 --> 00:29:57,540
She appeared at the end of the hallway with a clipboard pressed against her chest.

722
00:29:57,900 --> 00:29:59,720
And a wet charcoal colored dress.

723
00:29:59,900 --> 00:30:01,520
Her hair still damp from rain.

724
00:30:01,880 --> 00:30:05,420
Her mouth tense like someone who'd spent hours holding in a speech.

725
00:30:05,420 --> 00:30:08,500
She looked at me as if she were checking a catering order.

726
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:12,360
I scanned the three exits before I noticed the way she breathed.

727
00:30:12,760 --> 00:30:14,320
Scanning exits was muscle memory.

728
00:30:14,880 --> 00:30:19,700
Noticing the way she breathed was the first thing I'd done without deciding to in a long time.

729
00:30:20,040 --> 00:30:21,360
I remembered the ballroom.

730
00:30:21,820 --> 00:30:24,860
The moment the exfiance approached with a rehearsed line.

731
00:30:25,100 --> 00:30:26,740
And she answered with sarcasm.

732
00:30:27,380 --> 00:30:29,140
Before I even had to open my mouth.

733
00:30:29,600 --> 00:30:30,300
It was there.

734
00:30:30,640 --> 00:30:34,960
It was exactly there that something happened that I didn't have a name for in my vocabulary.

735
00:30:35,500 --> 00:30:38,280
I'd walked into that gala to identify a trader.

736
00:30:38,780 --> 00:30:41,820
And in four seconds a woman I'd never seen in my life.

737
00:30:42,100 --> 00:30:46,860
Had parried a public humiliation with the serenity of someone who had nothing left to lose.

738
00:30:47,300 --> 00:30:49,900
And still chose to defend herself with elegance.

739
00:30:50,380 --> 00:30:52,020
I knew how to identify courage.

740
00:30:52,540 --> 00:30:54,520
It had been my trade since I was 22.

741
00:30:55,220 --> 00:30:56,420
This was something else.

742
00:30:56,700 --> 00:30:59,480
This was a woman who laughed when she was about to cry.

743
00:30:59,920 --> 00:31:04,240
And I recognized the texture of that laugh before I even knew her full name.

744
00:31:04,240 --> 00:31:08,420
The service hallway came next, out of chronological order.

745
00:31:09,100 --> 00:31:10,000
The side door.

746
00:31:10,560 --> 00:31:15,160
The smell of flowers and of invisible work mixing in the air between the white walls.

747
00:31:15,660 --> 00:31:17,720
She said she didn't know who I was.

748
00:31:18,060 --> 00:31:22,240
I answered that she was the first person in a long time I didn't want to manipulate.

749
00:31:22,960 --> 00:31:23,800
It was true.

750
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:27,240
I hadn't predicted it would be true when I opened my mouth.

751
00:31:27,760 --> 00:31:31,580
Because the truth wasn't usually my starting point in any conversation.

752
00:31:31,580 --> 00:31:35,920
My fingers moved toward her face a millimeter before her chin rose.

753
00:31:36,640 --> 00:31:37,040
I stopped.

754
00:31:37,600 --> 00:31:38,280
She stopped.

755
00:31:38,840 --> 00:31:41,760
It was the first time in my life I stopped out of respect.

756
00:31:42,220 --> 00:31:42,940
Not calculation.

757
00:31:43,700 --> 00:31:44,740
And then the big screen.

758
00:31:45,360 --> 00:31:47,400
My face on national broadcast.

759
00:31:48,040 --> 00:31:49,920
The ballroom that froze in a second.

760
00:31:50,420 --> 00:31:52,780
The rivals coming in through the side doors.

761
00:31:53,300 --> 00:31:54,640
I could have left through the back.

762
00:31:55,080 --> 00:31:56,900
I'd had two roots mapped since arriving.

763
00:31:57,260 --> 00:31:58,140
It was the rule.

764
00:31:58,420 --> 00:31:59,660
It was always the rule.

765
00:31:59,660 --> 00:32:04,660
The first instruction of any family head was to preserve your own head above all else.

766
00:32:05,100 --> 00:32:06,680
I looked at her across the ballroom.

767
00:32:07,020 --> 00:32:09,740
She looked back at me with disgust, with fear.

768
00:32:10,240 --> 00:32:13,380
With the remnant of an anger that hadn't yet crashed down on me.

769
00:32:13,680 --> 00:32:14,420
And she stayed.

770
00:32:14,980 --> 00:32:15,860
She didn't run.

771
00:32:16,240 --> 00:32:20,360
She stayed with her feet planted on the marble of the ballroom she herself had organized.

772
00:32:20,960 --> 00:32:22,680
I stayed because she had stayed.

773
00:32:23,060 --> 00:32:28,200
It was the first time in my life I understood why my father used to say that silence was power.

774
00:32:28,200 --> 00:32:34,300
And that power was the only thing worth less than standing beside the person you choose to stand with.

775
00:32:34,520 --> 00:32:36,300
I opened my eyes over the sink.

776
00:32:36,740 --> 00:32:38,060
The water was still running.

777
00:32:38,580 --> 00:32:39,320
Cold now.

778
00:32:39,620 --> 00:32:41,880
And that was when the other memory came back.

779
00:32:42,340 --> 00:32:44,320
The one from the morning after the gala.

780
00:32:44,920 --> 00:32:46,960
The car pulling out of the hotel's basement.

781
00:32:47,480 --> 00:32:48,520
The engine low.

782
00:32:49,240 --> 00:32:50,600
Chicago streets still wet.

783
00:32:51,160 --> 00:32:52,340
Massimo in the back seat.

784
00:32:52,720 --> 00:32:53,160
Paternal.

785
00:32:53,740 --> 00:32:54,860
His shoulders relaxed.

786
00:32:54,860 --> 00:32:59,520
Smiling with that tenderness of someone who had raised me after my father's death.

787
00:32:59,840 --> 00:33:00,720
He said in Italian,

788
00:33:01,400 --> 00:33:02,420
You deserve it, son.

789
00:33:02,900 --> 00:33:05,860
With the calm of someone who believes every word he chooses.

790
00:33:06,460 --> 00:33:07,920
I smiled back that day.

791
00:33:08,360 --> 00:33:09,500
I squeezed his shoulder.

792
00:33:10,120 --> 00:33:11,380
I thought it was pride.

793
00:33:12,360 --> 00:33:13,400
22 years.

794
00:33:14,100 --> 00:33:18,440
Massimo had been at my side in every important decision I'd made as head of the family.

795
00:33:19,000 --> 00:33:22,860
Including the one that led me to pretend to be an escort to identify a traitor,

796
00:33:22,860 --> 00:33:24,740
laundering money through the event.

797
00:33:25,060 --> 00:33:28,880
The one who had convinced me with soft words and a father's patience

798
00:33:28,880 --> 00:33:32,820
that the traitor was inside the hotel and not inside my own office.

799
00:33:33,340 --> 00:33:34,260
Had been Massimo.

800
00:33:34,740 --> 00:33:35,980
I shut off the faucet.

801
00:33:36,540 --> 00:33:39,640
The sentence in the car weighed three times as much now.

802
00:33:39,880 --> 00:33:40,920
You deserve it, son.

803
00:33:41,440 --> 00:33:45,620
He said, deserve because he knew exactly what I didn't deserve to know.

804
00:33:45,860 --> 00:33:47,040
He said, son.

805
00:33:47,320 --> 00:33:52,140
Because 22 years earlier, he'd killed the man who was trying to give two women back their own names.

806
00:33:52,140 --> 00:33:57,060
I breathed in deep, once slow, through my nose.

807
00:33:57,580 --> 00:34:00,520
It was all I could allow myself without breaking something.

808
00:34:00,920 --> 00:34:04,360
When Everin came back from the kitchen, he didn't try to touch me.

809
00:34:04,620 --> 00:34:09,400
He sat at the other end of the couch, with a meter of space between us that neither of us had the

810
00:34:09,400 --> 00:34:13,360
energy to cross, and stayed looking at the floor with his elbows on his knees.

811
00:34:13,800 --> 00:34:16,900
I need a day, I said, before he tried anything.

812
00:34:17,460 --> 00:34:18,880
He nodded without lifting his head.

813
00:34:19,260 --> 00:34:20,260
Not to leave here.

814
00:34:20,260 --> 00:34:22,980
I added, because it was important to say it out loud.

815
00:34:23,400 --> 00:34:26,500
To breathe, stay, he said, low.

816
00:34:27,020 --> 00:34:28,280
The house is yours too.

817
00:34:28,600 --> 00:34:29,560
The house wasn't mine.

818
00:34:30,040 --> 00:34:32,480
The house belonged to a surname that had killed my father,

819
00:34:32,960 --> 00:34:35,640
through a man who still walked free, paternal,

820
00:34:36,160 --> 00:34:38,760
sitting at meeting tables with Everin on Tuesday mornings,

821
00:34:39,320 --> 00:34:40,800
probably with coffee and cookies.

822
00:34:41,320 --> 00:34:44,560
But at that moment, I didn't have the strength to correct the sentence.

823
00:34:45,060 --> 00:34:47,760
I had the rest of my father's tape somewhere in the world,

824
00:34:47,760 --> 00:34:51,920
a Malvani mother who had agreed to sleep far from her own home out of fear,

825
00:34:52,440 --> 00:34:56,940
and the name Masimo Grell pulsing behind my eyes like a light that wouldn't turn off no.

826
00:34:57,220 --> 00:34:58,640
Matter how much I tried.

827
00:34:59,160 --> 00:34:59,900
I got up.

828
00:35:00,240 --> 00:35:01,520
I walked to the guest room.

829
00:35:01,920 --> 00:35:05,120
I stopped in the doorway, hand on the frame and looked back.

830
00:35:05,560 --> 00:35:07,520
Everin was in the same position on the couch.

831
00:35:08,040 --> 00:35:11,060
His shoulders lowered for the first time in three months of penthouse,

832
00:35:11,540 --> 00:35:14,560
and shared dinners and silences that were good because they were chosen.

833
00:35:15,160 --> 00:35:16,860
Now the lowered shoulders weren't rest.

834
00:35:16,860 --> 00:35:20,080
They were the weight of an inheritance he hadn't asked for,

835
00:35:20,320 --> 00:35:22,860
and that someone had spent decades building on his shoulders

836
00:35:22,860 --> 00:35:25,280
without him knowing the real price.

837
00:35:25,960 --> 00:35:27,700
Masimo, I said out loud,

838
00:35:28,160 --> 00:35:31,980
because the first time needed to be between the two of us before anything else.

839
00:35:32,460 --> 00:35:38,060
Masimo, he repeated, with the same voice of someone confirming a sentence he already knew was coming.

840
00:35:38,480 --> 00:35:41,520
It was at that instant that his phone rang on the coffee table.

841
00:35:41,920 --> 00:35:45,200
We both looked at the same time, an involuntary reflex,

842
00:35:45,200 --> 00:35:48,160
as if the whole apartment had held its breath together.

843
00:35:48,700 --> 00:35:50,640
The screen lit up with the cold late night light.

844
00:35:51,040 --> 00:35:53,140
The name rose in clear letters on the display,

845
00:35:53,640 --> 00:35:55,780
as if it were a joke no one in the room had authorized.

846
00:35:56,500 --> 00:35:59,660
Masimo, Everin looked at me, I looked at him.

847
00:35:59,900 --> 00:36:02,740
He answered without bringing the phone to his face, on speaker.

848
00:36:03,320 --> 00:36:05,540
His thumb firm and motionless on the coffee table.

849
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:10,440
The voice came sweet, slow, an Italian first and then in English,

850
00:36:10,980 --> 00:36:15,180
with that precise tenderness of someone calling to ask whether his son had slept well,

851
00:36:15,180 --> 00:36:17,060
and whether he'd eaten anything.

852
00:36:18,140 --> 00:36:20,840
Everin, figliomio, your mother didn't come home.

853
00:36:21,280 --> 00:36:24,080
I got worried. Would you happen to know where she is?

854
00:36:24,400 --> 00:36:26,700
The cemetery that Monday morning was nearly empty.

855
00:36:27,060 --> 00:36:29,580
The sky had that washed out light of late spring.

856
00:36:30,080 --> 00:36:33,400
The kind that looks faded but burns your eyes if you look too long.

857
00:36:33,820 --> 00:36:37,540
And the wind came off the lake with the smell of still water and damp grass.

858
00:36:37,760 --> 00:36:42,260
I walked alone down the side lane, with a small bouquet of white daisies in my hand,

859
00:36:42,260 --> 00:36:45,860
because daisies were what my father always bought when he came home from work,

860
00:36:46,240 --> 00:36:48,540
with the excuse that he didn't have money for roses.

861
00:36:49,100 --> 00:36:51,180
He'd arrive home with the flowers a little crushed.

862
00:36:51,660 --> 00:36:56,020
The stem still slick with water, and put them in the jar by the kitchen sink as if that were

863
00:36:56,020 --> 00:36:59,920
enough for the whole week. It always was. His headstone was clean.

864
00:37:00,500 --> 00:37:04,220
I came twice a year, always quick, always without saying much.

865
00:37:04,540 --> 00:37:08,960
That morning, I crouched and took more time arranging the flowers than I needed to.

866
00:37:08,960 --> 00:37:13,020
Separating the stems one by one, straightening what was already straight.

867
00:37:13,580 --> 00:37:17,880
My hands needed something to do while I gathered the words. I didn't know Dad.

868
00:37:18,360 --> 00:37:23,400
My voice came out low, without theater. There was no one nearby. I could cry.

869
00:37:23,880 --> 00:37:26,720
It took me a few seconds to realize I wasn't going to.

870
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:29,880
For 22 years I called you the man who left us early.

871
00:37:30,240 --> 00:37:33,940
For 22 years I put on your account the bills mom paid alone.

872
00:37:33,940 --> 00:37:40,300
For 22 years I explained you from a distance to others as if you'd had no choice.

873
00:37:40,880 --> 00:37:44,100
I ran my thumb over the letter C of the surname engraved in the stone.

874
00:37:44,620 --> 00:37:50,260
The surface was cold, even in the morning sun. You had a choice. You chose us.

875
00:37:50,620 --> 00:37:55,480
I only found out too late to thank you the way I wanted to. I stayed crouched another minute.

876
00:37:55,900 --> 00:38:00,980
The wind stirred the daisies. The anger when it came was small and clear.

877
00:38:00,980 --> 00:38:06,640
Without smudges it wasn't Adam. It was at the man who had decided for both of them

878
00:38:06,640 --> 00:38:12,180
silently for years, using the name of a father that wasn't his to protect a power that

879
00:38:12,180 --> 00:38:17,380
should never have existed. I'm going to take care of this. I said, I don't know how yet.

880
00:38:18,260 --> 00:38:25,320
But I will. I stood up. The wind passed again. I wiped my hands on my pants and walked down the

881
00:38:25,320 --> 00:38:30,960
lane toward the gate without looking back. Dario was waiting for me, leaning against the black

882
00:38:30,960 --> 00:38:36,000
tree with the posture of someone who'd learned to take up the least space possible in any scenario.

883
00:38:36,640 --> 00:38:41,900
Dark suit even in early spring. Sun glasses. His tie loosened exactly one millimeter,

884
00:38:42,640 --> 00:38:47,100
which for him probably counted as a concession to the season. Sarai was in the passenger seat of

885
00:38:47,100 --> 00:38:52,780
her car behind his. With the window open and her hair pinned in a careless twist,

886
00:38:53,300 --> 00:38:56,920
reading something on her phone with the expression of someone pretending not to be paying

887
00:38:56,920 --> 00:39:02,480
attention to absolutely everything around her. I wasn't expecting you. I said, he asked.

888
00:39:03,040 --> 00:39:08,760
Dario answered, in his usual half-voice, controlled and without inflection. I figured it'd be

889
00:39:08,760 --> 00:39:13,240
simpler for me to bring it than to send it. He opened the trunk. He took out a sealed cardboard

890
00:39:13,240 --> 00:39:19,060
box, medium-sized, no label, packing tape run three times around the edges as if the

891
00:39:19,060 --> 00:39:23,560
contents demanded extra care. It weighed enough that both his arms compensated for the wait

892
00:39:23,560 --> 00:39:30,520
for an instant before adjusting. Everything is here. He said, everything he has. I looked at the box.

893
00:39:31,200 --> 00:39:37,200
At Dario. At the sky. Which still had that washed out light that chose nothing. Did he send a note?

894
00:39:37,580 --> 00:39:42,020
Dario took from the inner pocket of his jacket a folded card and handed it to me without

895
00:39:42,020 --> 00:39:48,600
ceremony. Evern's handwriting was straight. Firm. Without flourish. The capital letters a bit larger

896
00:39:48,600 --> 00:39:54,200
than necessary as if they were holding something behind them. You decide. I won't touch it.

897
00:39:54,420 --> 00:40:00,080
I put the card in my coat pocket. Close to my chest. Surai got out of the car with two cups of coffee

898
00:40:00,080 --> 00:40:04,800
and handed me one. Looking at me for a second with that silence she used when she didn't want me

899
00:40:04,800 --> 00:40:09,640
to know she was worried. Her glance passed quickly over Dario before returning to him with the

900
00:40:09,640 --> 00:40:15,240
speed of someone who tried not to look and hadn't managed to. Nice suit. Surai said,

901
00:40:15,240 --> 00:40:21,220
with a slanted smile. In the middle of a Chicago summer, who introduced you to summer around

902
00:40:21,220 --> 00:40:26,620
here creature. Dario turned his face slightly toward her. The dark glasses didn't let his eyes show.

903
00:40:27,040 --> 00:40:31,460
But the pause before his answer was long enough to be intentional. Do you feel hot?

904
00:40:31,880 --> 00:40:37,540
Surai pressed. Amused by her own advance. Do you always ask questions about other people's clothes?

905
00:40:38,200 --> 00:40:44,460
Dario shot back. Voice dry as paper. Surai laughed before the end of her own answer. The kind of

906
00:40:44,460 --> 00:40:50,340
laugh that doesn't wait for permission. Always. She said, it's my way of keeping my sanity in the

907
00:40:50,340 --> 00:40:55,580
middle of all this. They I'd each other for a second longer than necessary. It was the only thing in

908
00:40:55,580 --> 00:41:00,500
that whole morning that pulled a smile out of me. Surai took the box from Dario's hands without

909
00:41:00,500 --> 00:41:05,260
asking. As if the weight were in a fence she resolved before he could try to carry it back.

910
00:41:05,760 --> 00:41:11,400
Setted in the trunk of our car and slammed the lid with the palm of her hand. Let's go. She said

911
00:41:11,400 --> 00:41:16,660
to me. Ignoring Dario with the precision of someone very aware of his presence. There's a hotel

912
00:41:16,660 --> 00:41:23,380
office waiting for you. Dario nodded to me slightly. Not to her. He got into his own car, with the same

913
00:41:23,380 --> 00:41:29,600
contained gesture as always. And I had to look the other way, so I wouldn't smile again. The hotel's

914
00:41:29,600 --> 00:41:35,360
events office smelled of warm paper and old flowers. The residual scent of two arrangements I hadn't

915
00:41:35,360 --> 00:41:41,080
had changed the week before. It was the same room where I'd kept for months. The folder with the

916
00:41:41,080 --> 00:41:46,320
evidence against Calvin. The same dark wood shelf. The same lamp with the butter-colored shade

917
00:41:46,320 --> 00:41:51,200
that had needed a stronger bulb for at least two years. The same door with the lock that required

918
00:41:51,200 --> 00:41:56,320
a shove of the shoulder to close properly. I set everyone's box on top of the desk. The same

919
00:41:56,320 --> 00:42:02,120
gesture as before. Countless times. With Calvin's folder. The different weight. The completely

920
00:42:02,120 --> 00:42:08,200
different feeling. I opened it. Inside. Organized into subfolders numbered in Evelyn's handwriting

921
00:42:08,200 --> 00:42:14,660
on the labels. Was the entire empire. Casino contracts with coded clauses. Londering schemes that

922
00:42:14,660 --> 00:42:20,300
ran through charity events. At least four of them at hotels I knew by name. Names of council members.

923
00:42:20,800 --> 00:42:26,620
Of two mayors. Of a retired federal judge. Lists of monthly payments with dates and initials

924
00:42:26,620 --> 00:42:32,040
beside each entry. meticulous as clean bookkeeping. As if Everin had spent the last month's

925
00:42:32,040 --> 00:42:38,680
building. In silence and without telling me anything. The very dossier against himself. In a subfolder

926
00:42:38,680 --> 00:42:44,400
at the back. Separated from the others by a blue tab. Three thin envelopes with the label and

927
00:42:44,400 --> 00:42:50,820
tarot cross written by hand. Original documents. Copies of internal reports from the time. The

928
00:42:50,820 --> 00:42:56,540
complete transcription of a third witness's testimony that confirmed. Point by point. What Bruna

929
00:42:56,540 --> 00:43:02,000
had said the night before. I stayed looking at the envelopes longer than I expected to need. I held

930
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:06,780
my hands enough to clear my father's name before any camera in the country. And enough to send

931
00:43:06,780 --> 00:43:12,540
Everin to prison for the next 20 odd years. I sat in the chair. Surai sat on the edge of the desk

932
00:43:12,540 --> 00:43:17,980
at my side. Without joking. Without filling the silence with anything. She stayed there while I

933
00:43:17,980 --> 00:43:23,360
leaped through each subfolder. Slowly. Reading enough to understand what I was holding without

934
00:43:23,360 --> 00:43:29,000
needing to read it all to know the weight. You don't have to decide today. Surai said. After a

935
00:43:29,000 --> 00:43:35,780
long while. I know. But you're going to decide today. I know. She put her hand over mine for two seconds.

936
00:43:36,360 --> 00:43:41,320
Not a third. Which would have been too much for both of us. I've known you since you were 22

937
00:43:41,320 --> 00:43:47,080
know. You don't decide anything in an office. You decide over coffee. That was why I ended

938
00:43:47,080 --> 00:43:52,240
up inside the cafe in the hotel's neighborhood and hour later. With the box closed again under

939
00:43:52,240 --> 00:43:56,860
the table and the smell of espresso and cinnamon mixed with the low sound of music. No one was

940
00:43:56,860 --> 00:44:02,180
listening to. The view in the mirror behind the counter gave me back my face without makeup for the first

941
00:44:02,180 --> 00:44:07,920
time in weeks. I looked at the reflection. The reflection looked back at me with the same absent calm

942
00:44:07,920 --> 00:44:13,160
of someone who's already decided and hasn't yet told her own body. There was no longer the woman

943
00:44:13,160 --> 00:44:19,520
from the altar. There was no longer the radio headline. There was just me over a cup of black coffee.

944
00:44:20,120 --> 00:44:25,400
Deciding the rest of my own story with my hands wrapped around the warm cup. I thought about my father.

945
00:44:25,400 --> 00:44:31,280
I thought about everin. I thought about myself. In the exact order the things needed to be thought

946
00:44:31,280 --> 00:44:37,200
about. I stood up. I went back to the penthouse in the late afternoon with the box again in the

947
00:44:37,200 --> 00:44:43,240
passenger seat and the sun going down over the lake in tones of old copper. The kind of light that

948
00:44:43,240 --> 00:44:48,780
makes everything more beautiful and heavier at the same time. I rode up in the private elevator

949
00:44:48,780 --> 00:44:54,420
and silence with my own reflection accompanying me in the mirrored elevator door until the floor closed.

950
00:44:55,000 --> 00:44:58,620
I opened the door with the key he'd given me three months earlier.

951
00:44:59,480 --> 00:45:04,180
A friend was standing in the living room facing the window, phone in his lowered hand. He hadn't

952
00:45:04,180 --> 00:45:09,760
heard the door when he turned. His eyes were different. With a stillness that wasn't calm,

953
00:45:10,240 --> 00:45:14,600
it was the kind of stillness of someone who had just received news they'd waited their whole life

954
00:45:14,600 --> 00:45:20,660
for. Without knowing they were waiting. Massimo, he said simply, as if the name weighed enough

955
00:45:20,660 --> 00:45:25,500
not to need anything else around it. He took my mother. I stopped in the middle of the room.

956
00:45:26,020 --> 00:45:31,680
When, 40 minutes ago, he called just now. He once the box burned in 24 hours,

957
00:45:32,240 --> 00:45:37,980
filmed, in exchange for my mother. I set the box on the coffee table between the two of us.

958
00:45:38,340 --> 00:45:42,220
The sound of the wood receiving the weight filled the room for one full second,

959
00:45:42,780 --> 00:45:48,760
clean and definitive. Everin looked at the box. He looked at me. He said nothing for a while I

960
00:45:48,760 --> 00:45:54,460
didn't try to shorten. I sat on the couch. He sat in the armchair across from me. The box

961
00:45:54,460 --> 00:46:00,640
between us like a third body neither of us invited, but that was there. Present and motionless.

962
00:46:01,040 --> 00:46:06,380
Demanding an answer. The silence lasted three minutes. I didn't count because I needed to measure.

963
00:46:06,940 --> 00:46:11,940
I counted because it was the first time in 22 years that two entire surnames,

964
00:46:12,420 --> 00:46:17,580
cross and malvani. Sad in the same room without anyone trying to defend themselves from the other.

965
00:46:17,580 --> 00:46:21,760
His fingers moved slowly over the tabletop, without apparent purpose,

966
00:46:22,380 --> 00:46:26,100
until they reached the edge of the box. My fingers came to the other end,

967
00:46:26,660 --> 00:46:31,080
almost without deciding. Our thumbs came close to touching. They stopped there,

968
00:46:31,380 --> 00:46:37,020
less than a centimeter apart without touching. We're not going to burn it. I said. He lifted his eyes

969
00:46:37,020 --> 00:46:41,600
with a slowness that told me he already knew I was going to say that, and was waiting anyway.

970
00:46:42,020 --> 00:46:47,080
We're going to record him saying it. I finished. Everin stayed looking at me for a while.

971
00:46:47,080 --> 00:46:53,700
Without asking how, without asking why. Just looking. In that way, he'd had since the first time

972
00:46:53,700 --> 00:46:59,900
backstage at the hotel. Months earlier, when he scanned the room's three exits before scanning me,

973
00:47:00,080 --> 00:47:07,240
and then completely forgot the exits. When he asked, there's day night at the hotel. I'll set up

974
00:47:07,240 --> 00:47:12,370
a private donor's event in the smaller ballroom. His allies will be invited. He'll come because he

975
00:47:12,370 --> 00:47:18,950
comes to the hotel's events. I lead it. You wait. Dario. Dario coordinates parallel security.

976
00:47:19,710 --> 00:47:25,610
Sir I works the catering. I talk to Massimo in a side room. Sealing microphones. The old ones

977
00:47:25,610 --> 00:47:32,130
still installed from last year's retrofit. He nodded once. Slowly. And my mother? The police

978
00:47:32,130 --> 00:47:37,690
moving on the warehouse when the confession is closed. You go in first, alone, to make sure she's

979
00:47:37,690 --> 00:47:42,350
alive when the door opens. He looked at me for a long while. His eyes running over my

980
00:47:42,350 --> 00:47:47,290
face is if searching for a fracture in the plan or in me. You know what you're asking me to do.

981
00:47:47,610 --> 00:47:53,370
I know. I'm going to lose everything. I know. I'm not asking you to give up. He said,

982
00:47:53,810 --> 00:47:58,090
and his voice came out lower than I expected. With a layer underneath that wasn't weakness,

